{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"896","authors":[{"fullname":"David Germano","id":"2"}],"title":"An Overview of the Drukpa Kagy\u00fc Tradition","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:05:49 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:05:49 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p>The numerous Drukpa Kagy\u00fc ('brug pa bka' brgyud) sects draw their name from the Drukpa ('brug pa) monastery in southern Tibet founded by Tsangpa Gyar\u00e9 (gtsang pa rgya ras, 1161-1211), also known as Pelden Drukpa Rinpoche Yesh\u00e9 Dorj\u00e9 (dpal ldan 'brug pa rin po che ye shes rdo rje, 1161-1211). He himself was a disciple of Lingrepa Pema Dorj\u00e9 (gling ras pa pad ma rdo rje, 1128-88). G\u00f6tsangpa (rgod tshang pa) is a major successor of Tsangpa Gyar\u00e9. Pema Karpo (pad ma dkar po, 1527-1592) is one of the more important Drukpa Kagy\u00fc authors historically. The Drukpa Kagy\u00fc tradition eventually came to be dominant in Bhutan, where it is currently the official state religion equivalent to the status the Geluk sect enjoyed in Central Tibet prior to the Chinese takeover in 1959.<\/p>","title":"An Overview of the Drukpa Kagy\u00fc Tradition"}]}
